lot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1322–":"1322–Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1322–Male":"1322–Deceased","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Quemeford Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bellot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Benito, Manuel, Alejandra, Felipe, Jovita, Juan, Maricela, Pedro.","Catalan: from a diminutive of <b>Belló</b> (see   Bello  ).","French: nickname from a derivative of   Bel   ‘beautiful’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bello","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Manuel, Juan, Jorge, Mario, Roberto, Eduardo, Sergio, Alberto, Ernesto, Julio.  Portuguese Joaquim, Paulo.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Natale, Vito, Eliseo, Luciano, Sal, Aldo, Amato.","Spanish and Italian: from <i>bello</i> ‘handsome’ (from Late Latin <i>bellus</i>), hence a nickname for a handsome man or perhaps in some instances ironically for an ugly one. In medieval Italy the word was also applied as an omen or well-wishing name.","Catalan (<b>Belló</b>): shortened form of <b>Abelló</b> (see   Abello  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bellot was born in 1322, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Belet, was 28 and his mother, Mrs Robert Belet, was 33. He had at least 1 son with Lady Robert Bellot."},"et":{"about 1322–":"1322–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Quemeford Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1322–":"1322–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Quemeford Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bellot, Norfolk,, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1322–":"1322–Décédé","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1322–Male":"1322–Décédé","1328–Female":"1328–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1295–1323":"1295–1323","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","about 1322":"1322","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Quemeford Caine Wi